Marty,

BBS's which are basically service hosts will probably not move but
the view that only BBS's will be true hosts on AMPRNET is incorrect.
I myself want a host and I do massive amounts of driving between
Pittsburgh, Washington DC, Tampa FL, New York and Philadelphia. I
don't believe a network design should prohibit me from having a
powerful computer in my car that can receive mail while I am away
from the car.

Therefore believing you can assign names based on static location and
use that information for an advantage is wrong. Of course, if you are
using the person's initial address to create a form of delegation of
work (so multiple people around the country can handle registration
of names) then assigning many levels will undoubtedly be too inhuman
and too misleading (people will tend to believe the name implies the
current person's address if it specified to the house number).

I call myself Rudy Nedved not 
Rudy.Nedved.5607.Fair.Oaks.St.Pittsburgh.PA.15217-1033.US. People
want short names and software wants long exact names. There is
enough computing power to have a compromise. I can certainly deal
with NEDVED.PITTSBURGH.PA.US. 

-Rudy

